      <listPlace>
	<place xml:id="Pauni">
	  <placeName type="modern" xml:lang="mar-Latn">Pauni</placeName>
	  <idno type="viaf">http://viaf.org/viaf/243855978</idno>
	  <location>
	    <geo>79.636416 20.793791</geo>
	  </location>
	  <desc>A few sculptures and inscriptions were discovered here in 1968. Subsequently it became clear that Pauni was the site of an ancient Buddhist stūpa. The stūpa was beneath a mound on which a temple of Jagannātha had been constructed. <bibl><ptr target="bibl:Deo1972"/></bibl> refers to two principal sites, Jagannātha Ṭekḍī and Chaṇḍakāpur Ṭekḍī.</desc>
	  <listPlace type="subsidiary">
	    <place xml:id="Jagannāthaṭekḍī">
	      <placeName type="modern" xml:lang="mar-Latn">Jagannātha Ṭekḍī</placeName>
	      <desc>Jagannātha Ṭekḍī is a mound, so named because it was the site of the temple of Jagannātha. It is the main <hi rend="italic">stūpa</hi> site, where all of the inscriptions have been found.</desc>
	    </place>
	    <place xml:id="Chaṇḍakāpurṭekḍī">
	      <placeName type="modern" xml:lang="mar-Latn">Chaṇḍakpur Ṭekḍī</placeName>
	      <desc>Chaṇḍakāpur Ṭekdī is a smaller mound at Pauni which was also excavated by Deo and his team.</desc>
	    </place>
	  </listPlace>
	</place>
      </listPlace>
